ly analytic, the volume also includes essays deeply informed by psychoanalysis, phenomenology, and feminist and social theory. The fourteen chapters in this collection address three interrelated questions: What is racism? What are the causes of racism? And what are the moral and political implications of racism? Although their approaches are wide ranging, the contributors to Racism in Mind broadly endorse a psychological-characterological approach to the understanding of many aspects of racism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRacism. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAltman, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlum, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoxill, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDummett, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia, J. L.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaslanger, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLa Caze, Marguerite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLengbeyer, Lawrence A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Michael P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Michael P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPataki, Tamas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPataki, Tamas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThomas, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTiemann, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWillett, Cynthia, e